social_posts.post_text: Brushes work pretty great most of the time. But sometimes you just have to use your fingers.
Let’s zoom in and out with this painting. Just for fun!

Elves are everywhere! In a mostly serious attempt to gain access to the landscape inside of my paintings I have imagined these creatures into the place I could not go. As I look around at them and imagine what it’s like to be them, I get to be inside the paintings too. And who doesn’t want to explore a colorful kaleidoscopic adventure park with elves, mushrooms and white rabbits? I’ll tell you, no one, thats who!
Come along as I paint a little psychedelic mushroom harvesting elf hanging upside down from its knees.
I’m considering making some wallpaper to install behind my paintings for the next show (opening Feb 25th @quintgallery ). Which of these three designs is your favorite? One, two or three?

This is a studio shot from a few weeks ago. Sometimes you see what you have been looking at for months/years and not seeing. This was one of those moments for me so I took a picture to see if I could see that quality of seeing in a photograph. I could not but it was still a nice picture!

I started out at symmetry and ended up at soap. All one! This is not an advertisement just cosmic coincidence. @drbronner (note: see this painting and a bunch of other new ones @quintgallery Feb 25th)

Sharing a new, almost finished painting. “Always Already Here”. This and a bunch of other new paintings will be at my next show @quintgallery opening Feb 25th. Shoot the gallery a DM if you want to be put in the preview list.

Is this, or is this not a poem? Not a good one, just one 😂.

I have to paint this line
this is just one line of many, many lines
but all I got to do is paint just this one
so many more to do
so many that I have done
but all I have to do is paint just this one

Sometimes (rarely) painting ideas come through fully formed. This little painting was one of those. It didn’t really fit with my most recent show but it demanded to be made and I relented. It was way too cute to ignore! 12x 18in acrylic on board. In view @quintgallery now.

There is something mysteriously important about symmetry. It can be used to guide physicists and mathematicians to new discoveries, bees to nectar and help a predator spot its prey out of the noise of a forest environment. It’s pretty rad! So I wondered if it’s useful to so many divergent interests can it also be helpful to an artist. Can it help me make a painting? That’s what my new show “Cosmic Symmetries” ( @quintgallery ) is all about an investigation into weather or not symmetry is useful to help make a picture. Photo credit: @lilekl9

It’s important to make sure your paintings are level and free of dirty finger smudges before a show. Lots of people don’t know that this is the required method for checking the bottom of the painting for both. An artists life is not always easy. My show “cosmic symmetries” is up @quintgallery in La Jolla until April 8th. Stop by and check the bottoms of all the paintings using this same method, you will see how well it works! Video credit: @lilekl9

I will be at the Ackland Art Museum ( @ackland_art_museum ) UNC-Chappel Hill tomorrow (Friday, March 31st ) to have a conversation about art and science with Professor Allen Anderson. All the info below:

Artist Conversation: Art / Science / Music / Math
Friday, March 31, 2023 | 3:30 p.m.–4:30 p.m.
Ackland Art Museum
This event requires
RSVP
Join us for a lively conversation between visiting artist Kelsey Brookes and composer Allen Anderson about the intersections of art, science, music, and math.
Brookes is a former scientist whose work One Pointed Attention 2 (2014), a large-scale painting based on the Fibonacci sequence, is on loan to the Ackland through the Art Bridges Collection Loan Partnership program.
Anderson’s compositions are often multimedia and interdisciplinary, responding to artworks or the natural environment. In addition to the spoken conversation, Anderson will debut a short musical composition written in response to Brookes’s painting on view in the Ackland’s galleries.
Tickets are free, but space is limited. Register below!

Presented in connection with the Art Bridges Collection Loan Partnership and the North Carolina Science Festival.

I titled this painting “Cook Book For A Sacred Life” after the final chapter in the Ram Dass book “Be Here Now”. When I first encountered this book as a teen I didn’t understand any of the concept, I just loved the illustrations. Since then, I have practiced both yoga and meditation and I understand some of the concepts but the book still has so much to offer and I am still blow away by the illustrations. The same way that chapter offers practical advice for pursuing a spiritual path in ones life, this paintings has been guiding me since I made it a few months ago so the title just seemed fitting. 

It is also the last few days to see “Cosmic Symmetries” @quintgallery so if you haven’t made it out yet now is the time!

social_posts.post_text:
If one pays close attention to conscious experience and asks themselves “where am I located within this experience”, surprising answers may be discovered. In the same way if one closely examines this painting hidden entities may be discovered. Elves and mushrooms made by the same black and white lines that make up the painting and they in turn manipulate, shape and bringing the painting into existence. In the case of closely examining ones conscious experience, I will leave that beautiful discovery for you to uncover.

“Centerless Awareness”
36x48in 
Acrylic on Canvas
For more info contact: @quintgallery

The shape of a line can encode an infinity of messages. When I am making a painting I am always asking myself what is this shape saying to me, how do I feel when I look at it? For this painting I was interested in the idea of doorways as a marker of transition from one space to another. Some doorways are simple and utilitarian some are ornate signifying a deeper transition. In my research I stumbled on this photograph of a temple door in Angkor Wat (Cambodia) and was inspired. I shaped the outside of my painting using the temple doorways as template. Finally, I was left with the center. Symmetry in the natural world can signify importance; living creatures are often symmetrical where as the surrounding environment often is not. Symmetry has been used by scientists to discover fundamental forces in the universe, by computer scientists to write code that generates this cyber space we are communicating in right now. It is important in a surprising way. Satisfied that symmetry was interesting enough I painted the center using a bilateral symmetry, the same symmetry that our bodies use to take shape and the painting was finished.

“Turtle Door”
60x84in 
Acrylic on Canvas
For more info contact: @quintgallery

What makes up the first person experience of self? When I examine my conscious experience I can recognize two things; thoughts and bodily sensations. I’m not completely sure that my bodily sensations are not just thoughts about bodily sensation but let’s put that to the side for the time being. Once thoughts and sensations are recognized what is left? I am sure lots has been said about what is left by people in a much better position to say so, but I made this painting about the sensation I have of what is left and titled it “pure seeing”. 

“Pure Seeing”
72in. diameter
Acrylic on Canvas
For more info contact: @quintgallery

The universal prescription for everything these days is to be “present”. From Buddhist philosophy to self help the present is everywhere and its big business. Why do we need to be guided to the present moment? If it’s the only place where we can ever be how can we fail to see it? How is it hidden in plain site? Some say its obscured by desire, others say it’s complete identification with thought that does it. Im not exactly sure but it definitely feels like a funny idea to have to be guided to the one thing that is never escapable. This painting is not an answer to anything, it is not a question either, it is about the interaction of all the components of consciousness. The present moment, desire and identification with thought, all of it. It’s a celebration of the giant messy ball of consciousness and its title is, like the present moment, “Always Already Here”.

“Always Already Here”
36x48in 
Acrylic on Canvas
For more info contact: @quintgallery

Work In Progress; The last show that I did I experimented with painting background gradients which was especially challenging and fun using acrylic paints. Those experiments left me wondering if I could also create foreground gradients? I experimented with different of ways to do that and this is one of those experiments. More work to do but I think you can kind of see where Im trying to go with this. 

Why is it that every time I come up with a painting idea it makes my paintings more labor intensive instead of less? Anyone have any thoughts?

A painting I made of a cobweb in 2019 as part of my research into form constants. I wanted to know why it was that many people reported seeing similar “images” when hallucinating. Im a long way from an expert on the subject but what I found was that we all share similar anatomical structures in our eyes, nerves and visual cortex and those structures “glitch” in similar ways leading to our shared “form constant” perceptions.

Watching this in reverse reminded me of just how much work the brush does to augment the motion of the painters hand. Translating all those body movements into fluid painted lines is a lot of work. Thank you little brush.
Studio shot from a while back. Photo credit @chase_crz
I don’t always match my paintings but when I do I always get a photo of it. Most of the time. Anyone guess the molecule I’m painting?

60x84in painting of a psilocybin molecule (in progress in this photo but now finished). It’s amazing how drastically our societies perception of this molecule has changed in the last 10 years. From dangerous enemy to medicine of promise. Sure hope this works out for us and the little psilocybin molecule.

I have struggled for months working out how to finish off the terminal points in these new gradient paintings. Then, following a lot of experimentation and trial and error, I realized if I extended the points and had them interact and group together it felt right. Progress often seems to follow a pattern in painting, experimentation via trial and error and then judging that product using feeling. There is no substitution for effort and experimentation in my estimation. So if you don’t know what to do, experiment!
Let’s paint some lines on this rainbow colored molecule. The center of each of the circles is the location of an atom in a MDMA molecule.
Studio shot from 2018.

Work in progress. This is a painting of 3,4-Methyl​enedioxy​methamphetamine (MDMA), commonly known as ecstasy. I wanted to show the approximate molecular orbits of each atom as well as illustrate the movement and energy present in this important medicine. The larger orbits are the carbon, nitrogen and oxygen atoms, the thin wispy ones are hydrogen. The hydrogens are the most fun to paint.

36x48in 
Acrylic on Canvas
2023
Studio shot from 2013. Photo credit: @chase_crz

Making some more progress on this new molecular orbitals painting of a 3,4-Methyl​enedioxy​methamphetamine (MDMA) molecule. The thin lines that highlight the hydrogen atoms orbits are my favorite to paint. They tell me where to go all I have to do is listen.
I realized that my sweater kind of  matched this new painting yesterday and then spent over an hour trying to capture that matching in a photograph! 🤣😂

The simple process of making a line. One at a time, over and over again. It might not seem like much but those little lines add up over time to create something much greater that the sum of each little line. I’m still completely enchanted by that magic synergy. *note; the area I am painting here is about 1x1in.
Photo of a Methylphenidate molecule I painted in 2013. Brand name: Ritalin
I wish I could fly around inside of these paintings. Until that becomes possible, which I’m sure it will be one day, zooming in will have to do. Swipe right to zoom!

I have been interested in doilies for the last few years. They look like they must have been inspired by a visual hallucination. Just like one of Heinrich Kluvers form constants but I have yet to find a direct connection in the literature search I have done, anyone out there know of a connection or someone discussing the topic of doilies and visual hallucination?

Anyway, this is my first attempt at painting about this topic as well as the first time I have used this new foreground gradient technique. I first came up with this technique a decade or more ago but ignored it because of its laborious nature. I rediscovered it this year and have reluctantly been working with it for the last 6 months or so. It takes forever to do but I like the clean simplicity it offers.
Wait for it! Big blue with some birds. 💙

How does one make sense of reality? Objective vs subjective, empiricism vs feeling, there are so many seemingly opposing methodologies. @zanemeyer from @chopemdownfilms came by the studio earlier this year as I was preparing for my show @quintgallery to talk about it. For what it’s worth I try to understand them all and apply where appropriate. It’s good to have lots of tools to help us feel through this deeply complex space we call life. Thank you @zanemeyer for trying to make sense of my blabbering 💛.

@zanemeyer from @chopemdownfilms stopped by the studio the other day and brought his film camera. On the way out the door he asked if me and my kids, who I had just picked up from school, wanted a shot. I’m so happy he did. I don’t know how these kids have got so big but it took seeing this photo to really see it. Just yesterday they were tiny. Thanks Zane! Not pictured here is my loving hard working beautiful wife @el_ppb

Here is an animation of a Harmine molecule I made with @chase_crz a few years ago. The animation was inspired by a print I made with @louisbuhl around the same time. 

Harmine has an amazing history! In 1905, the Colombian naturalist and chemist, Rafael Zerda-Bayón suggested the name telepathine to the then unknown hallucinogenic ingredient in ayahuasca brew. "Telepathine" comes from "telepathy", as Zerda-Bayón believed that ayahuasca induced telepathic visions. Many other names where suggested over the years but a consensus finally settled on Harmine as a name for this special molecule.

Last Episode of 2023! 

Super excited to end the first year of “Concerning The Spiritual in Art” with a powerful conversation with @kelseybrookes ! 

Episode 31

“States Of Awe with Kelsey Brookes

In this episode Kelsey and I discuss the origins of his art , stemming from his time working as a scientist and how his interests and passions for art took him on a winding unexpected journey to where he is today. We discuss the intersection of science and art, sacred geometry , and the mystery of consciousness. We talk about his approach to his work and its relationship with meditation, along with the importance of gratitude and the experience of awe in everyday life.  It was such a fun and rich discussion that you all are going to love!
